<DOC><DOCNO> AP900614-0121 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-90 1736EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r e AM-HarlemDance     06-14 0206</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Harlem Dance,0213</SECOND><HEAD>Harlem Dance Company Gets $1 Million Grant</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Dance Theater of Harlem, the ballet companythat canceled two tours this year because a financial crisis,received a $1 million conditional grant Thursday.   The Lila Wallace-Reader's Digest Fund will give $600,000 to helpreduce the company's deficit and $400,000 for dancers' salaries andcompany operations _ provided the company raises additional fundsby Sept. 30, the end of its fiscal year, said M. Christine DeVita,president of the fund.   Officials declined to say how much money the company needed toraise.   In January, after two tours by the company were canceled, theboard voted to cancel the New York season and lay off 51 dancers.   ``The Dance Theater of Harlem is a world-class ballet companyand clearly a national treasure,'' DeVita said. ``Given the fund'sinterest in building bridges between artists and communities, wewould be remiss if we did not come forward to help DTH.''   The Dance Theater of Harlem was the first American balletcompany to tour the Soviet Union and for two decades it hasperformed on stages around the world.   Its artistic director is Arthur Mitchell, former principaldancer with the New York City Ballet.</TEXT></DOC>